Encapsulation bundles data and the methods that operate on that data, and restricts direct access to some components using access modifiers or conventions. It protects invariants and supports information hiding.

Python:
class Bank:
 def __init__(self): self._balance = 0 # '_' signals internal
 def deposit(self, amt):
 if amt <= 0: raise ValueError('positive')
 self._balance += amt
 @property
 def balance(self): return self._balance

Java:
class Bank { private int balance=0; public void deposit(int a){ if(a<=0) throw new IllegalArgumentException(); balance+=a;} public int getBalance(){return balance;} }

C++:
class Bank { int balance{0}; public: void deposit(int a){ if(a<=0) throw std::invalid_argument("+"); balance+=a;} int getBalance() const { return balance; } };

Abstraction exposes essential behavior while hiding unnecessary details. It's achieved via abstract classes, interfaces, and well-designed APIs.

Python:
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
class Notifier(ABC):
 @abstractmethod
 def send(self, msg): ...

Java:
interface Notifier { void send(String msg); }

C++:
struct Notifier { virtual void send(const std::string&)=0; virtual ~Notifier()=default; };

Inheritance lets a class acquire behavior and state from a parent (base) class. Prefer composition when inheritance does not model an 'is-a' relationship or would increase coupling.

Python:
class Animal: pass
class Dog(Animal): pass

Java:
class Animal {}
class Dog extends Animal {}

C++:
struct Animal{}; struct Dog: Animal {};

Favor composition to assemble behaviors at runtime instead of deep inheritance hierarchies. Composition reduces coupling and avoids fragile base class problems.

Python:
class Car:
 def __init__(self, engine): self.engine=engine
 def drive(self): self.engine.run()

Java:
class Car { private Engine engine; Car(Engine e){this.engine=e;} void drive(){engine.run();} }

C++:
struct Car{ Engine engine; void drive(){ engine.run(); } };

Static members belong to the class, not instances; instance members are per-object. Static methods cannot access instance state unless an instance is provided.

Python:
class A: @staticmethod
 def util(): ...
 @classmethod
 def from_x(cls,x): return cls()

Java:
static int count; static void util(){}

C++:
struct A{ static int count; }; int A::count=0;

Generics (Java), templates (C++) and duck typing/generics (Python) enable parametric polymorphism. Arrays are covariant in Java (unsafe); generics are invariant (use ? extends/? super). C++ templates are compile-time and T is unconstrained unless concepts used.

Python:
from typing import Protocol
class Notifier(Protocol):
 def send(self, msg:str) -> None: ...

Java:
List r; List w;

C++:
template void sort(std::vector & v);

